# No Hardcoded Derived Values

When a value comes from a shared constant, array, or enum, always reference the source rather than duplicating the literal.

## Why

If the source changes (e.g. subtypes are renamed, reordered, or reformatted), hardcoded copies silently become stale and cause bugs in unrelated files.

## Examples

```tsx
// ❌ BAD -- hardcoded default that drifts when SUBTYPES changes
const [subtype, setSubtype] = useState("Checking");

// ✅ GOOD -- derived from the source of truth
const [subtype, setSubtype] = useState(SUBTYPES["depository"][0]);
```

```python
# ❌ BAD -- duplicating enum values as raw strings
if account.type in ["depository", "investment", "real_estate"]:

# ✅ GOOD -- reference the enum
if account.type in (AccountType.DEPOSITORY, AccountType.INVESTMENT, AccountType.REAL_ESTATE):
```

## Verification

After editing, spot-check for newly introduced literals that match known constants:

```bash
rg '"Checking"|"Savings"|"depository"|"investment"' frontend/
```

## Rule of thumb

If you're typing a string that also exists in a constant, import, or enum elsewhere in the codebase -- reference that symbol instead.
